<br>
The point of my post was just to be sarcastic.<br>
<br>
However, I believe that EQ would be better without items and characters being auctioned for real world dollars.  I think that it adds an uncomfortable element to the game.<br>
<br>
Let's look at the SoD for instance.  How do you think the seller's guildmate's feel about that?  How will it effect future decisions.  MainRaidTank01 retires, the cool thing to do is to pass it down to the guild.  Does he do that?  Or does he decide to sell?  Maybe he wouldn't normally sell, but can he really trust the guy that it's going to get passed down to?  Is he going to sell it, or the guy after him?<br>
<br>
Like I said, it adds an uncomfortable element to the game.  I personally do not like the notion of playing the game with people who play the game for a living to make money.<br>
<br>
I passed my Donals BP back to IV when I took a break and ended up getting screwed over when I returned by someone who I trusted.  I *think* that it was ebayed and that may have been the motive for it not being returned to me.  Ironically, that kind of kaka is what contributed to me selling Ceros, even though I always told myself that I wouldn't.<br>
<br>
